results.name: Number of complete orderless tree-factorizations of n >= 2.
comment: An orderless tree-factorization (see A292504 for definition) is complete if all leaves are prime numbers. This sequence first differs from A281119 at a(64)=33.
a(n) depends only on the prime signature of n. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Nov 18 2018
link: Andrew Howroyd, Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10000
formula: a(p^n) = A000669(n) for prime p. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Nov 18 2018
program: (PARI) seq(n)={my(v=vector(n), w=vector(n)); v[1]=1; for(k=2, n, w[k]=v[k]+isprime(k); forstep(j=n\k*k, k, -k, my(i=j, e=0); while(i%k==0, i/=k; e++; v[j]+=binomial(e+w[k]-1, e)*v[i]))); w[2..n]} \\ _Andrew Howroyd_, Nov 18 2018
results.author: _Gus Wiseman_, Sep 17 2017
